# Transaction Typestate

## Task
Implement the Transaction type with compile-time state machine using PhantomData.

## Type-Level State Machine (INV-STORE-001, spec §1.3)
```
Building → Committed → Applied
   ↓           ↓          ↓
 mutable    immutable   immutable
 add datoms  sealed     has receipt
```

Invalid transitions are COMPILE ERRORS, not runtime errors.

## Implementation (from guide/01-store.md §1.2)
```rust
pub struct Building;
pub struct Committed;
pub struct Applied;
pub trait TxState: sealed::Sealed {}
impl TxState for Building {}
impl TxState for Committed {}
impl TxState for Applied {}

pub struct TxData {
    pub tx_entity: EntityId,
    pub provenance: ProvenanceType,
    pub causal_predecessors: Vec<TxId>,
    pub agent: AgentId,
    pub rationale: String,
}

pub struct Transaction<S: TxState> {
    datoms: Vec<Datom>,
    tx_data: TxData,
    _state: PhantomData<S>,
}

impl Transaction<Building> {
    pub fn new(agent: AgentId) -> Self;
    pub fn assert_datom(&mut self, e: EntityId, a: Attribute, v: Value);
    pub fn retract_datom(&mut self, e: EntityId, a: Attribute, v: Value);
    pub fn commit(self, schema: &Schema) -> Result<Transaction<Committed>, TxValidationError>;
}

impl Transaction<Committed> {
    // apply() is called by Store::transact() — not public
}

impl Transaction<Applied> {
    pub fn tx_id(&self) -> TxId;
    pub fn datoms(&self) -> &[Datom];
    pub fn receipt(&self) -> &TxReceipt;
}
```

## Algebraic Significance
The typestate pattern encodes the transaction lifecycle as a type-level state machine.
This is the Rust encoding of the formal specification's "transaction phases" — there is
no way to apply an uncommitted transaction or modify a committed one. The compiler enforces
the spec at zero runtime cost.

## Sealed Trait Pattern
The sealed module prevents external implementation of TxState:
```rust
mod sealed { pub trait Sealed {} }
impl sealed::Sealed for Building {}
impl sealed::Sealed for Committed {}
impl sealed::Sealed for Applied {}
```

## Verification
V:TYPE — invalid state transitions don't compile (verified by trybuild or similar)

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Transaction<Building> allows assert_datom/retract_datom
- [ ] Transaction<Committed> cannot be constructed without .commit()
- [ ] Transaction<Applied> cannot be constructed without Store::transact()
- [ ] TxState trait is sealed (external implementations won't compile)
- [ ] commit() validates against schema and returns TxValidationError on failure

## Traces To
spec/01-store.md §1.3, guide/01-store.md §1.2 (Transaction Three-Box)

