[AUDIT-R3 HIGH FIX] commit() requires Store reference for causal predecessor validation.

The Transaction<Building> → Transaction<Committed> transition must validate that all
causal predecessors referenced by the transaction actually exist in the store. This means
commit() cannot be a pure method on Transaction — it needs read access to the Store.

CORRECTED API:
  impl Transaction<Building> {
      /// Seal the transaction. Validates causal predecessors exist in store.
      /// Returns Committed transaction ready for apply().
      pub fn commit(self, store: &Store) -> Result<Transaction<Committed>, KernelError> {
          // 1. Verify all predecessor TxIds exist in store
          for pred in &self.predecessors {
              if !store.contains_tx(pred) {
                  return Err(KernelError::Store(StoreErrorKind::MissingPredecessor(*pred)));
              }
          }
          // 2. Generate TxId via HLC
          let tx_id = store.hlc().tick();
          // 3. Freeze datom set, compute content hash
          Ok(Transaction { state: PhantomData::<Committed>, tx_id, datoms: self.datoms, ... })
      }
  }

  impl Transaction<Committed> {
      /// Apply to store. This is the only way to add datoms.
      pub fn apply(self, store: &mut Store) -> Result<TxReport, KernelError> { ... }
  }

ALTERNATIVE CONSIDERED: commit() takes no store, apply() does all validation.
REJECTED: Typestate's value is catching errors at the earliest possible transition.
If commit() doesn't validate, the Committed state is meaningless.

NOTE: The HLC lives inside the Store (INV-STORE-007), so commit() needs &Store anyway.

V:TYPE — commit(self, store: &Store) signature compiles
V:PROP — commit with invalid predecessor returns Err

[AUDIT-R3 MEDIUM FIX] Index key composition must include Op.

Per spec/01-store.md §1.5, the four covering indexes are:
  EAVT(o): (entity, attribute, value, tx, op) — primary, entity-centric lookups
  AEVT(o): (attribute, entity, value, tx, op) — attribute-centric, schema queries
  AVET(o): (attribute, value, entity, tx, op) — value lookups, uniqueness checks
  VAET(o): (value, attribute, entity, tx, op) — reverse refs (where value is Ref type)

The Op field is ALWAYS the final discriminant in every index because:
  - A datom [e, a, v, tx, assert] and [e, a, v, tx, retract] are DIFFERENT datoms
  - Without Op in the key, retractions would collide with assertions
  - The BTreeMap key must be the complete 5-tuple to maintain set semantics

Index implementation (in-memory, Stage 0):
  type EavtIndex = BTreeMap<(EntityId, Keyword, Value, TxId, Op), ()>;
  type AevtIndex = BTreeMap<(Keyword, EntityId, Value, TxId, Op), ()>;
  type AvetIndex = BTreeMap<(Keyword, Value, EntityId, TxId, Op), ()>;
  type VaetIndex = BTreeMap<(Value, Keyword, EntityId, TxId, Op), ()>;

Using () as the value because the key IS the datom — the index IS the store.
The EAVT index is the canonical representation; others are derived views.

LIVE INDEX UPDATE (INV-STORE-010): On each apply():
  for datom in tx.datoms() {
      self.eavt.insert((datom.e, datom.a, datom.v, datom.tx, datom.op), ());
      self.aevt.insert((datom.a, datom.e, datom.v, datom.tx, datom.op), ());
      // ... etc for AVET, VAET
  }
  // LIVE = monotone function: store grows → indexes grow. Never remove entries.

V:TYPE — BTreeMap key tuples compile with Ord
V:PROP — index count equals datom count after any transaction sequence
V:KANI — insert never removes existing entries (monotonicity)

