# HLC Clock and Frontier (frontier.rs)

## Task
Implement the Hybrid Logical Clock for transaction ordering and the Frontier type
for tracking per-agent latest transactions.

## HLC Algorithm (ADR-STORE-004, INV-STORE-011)
```rust
pub struct HlcClock {
    last_wall: u64,    // last observed wall time
    logical: u32,       // logical counter for same-millisecond events
    agent: AgentId,     // this agent's identity
}

impl HlcClock {
    pub fn new(agent: AgentId) -> Self;

    /// Generate a new TxId, guaranteed > all previously generated TxIds
    pub fn tick(&mut self) -> TxId {
        let now = wall_clock_millis();
        if now > self.last_wall {
            self.last_wall = now;
            self.logical = 0;
        } else {
            self.logical += 1;
        }
        TxId { wall_time: self.last_wall, logical: self.logical, agent: self.agent }
    }

    /// Update clock after receiving a remote TxId (merge clocks)
    pub fn update(&mut self, remote: &TxId) {
        self.last_wall = self.last_wall.max(remote.wall_time);
        if self.last_wall == remote.wall_time {
            self.logical = self.logical.max(remote.logical) + 1;
        }
    }
}
```

## Frontier Type (INV-STORE-009)
```rust
pub type Frontier = HashMap<AgentId, TxId>;
```
The frontier records the latest TxId seen from each agent. It defines the causal "now"
for a given store replica. Frontier is durable: it must persist across save/load.

## Formal Properties
- INV-STORE-011: For any agent a, successive TxIds are strictly increasing:
  tick()_1 < tick()_2 < tick()_3 < ...
- INV-STORE-009: frontier persists across serialize/deserialize cycle
- HLC merges are commutative: update(a, update(b, c)) = update(b, update(a, c))
  for independent a, b (because max is commutative and associative)

## Stage 0 Simplification
At Stage 0 (single-agent CLI), the HLC is simpler: only one agent, so logical counter
only increments for same-millisecond transactions. The multi-agent merge (update) is
implemented but tested primarily via proptest with synthetic remote TxIds.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] HlcClock::tick() produces monotonically increasing TxIds
- [ ] HlcClock::update() merges remote clock correctly
- [ ] Frontier type defined as HashMap<AgentId, TxId>
- [ ] Frontier merge: pointwise max per agent
- [ ] proptest: tick() > all previous ticks (even with clock regression)
- [ ] proptest: HLC merge is commutative

## Traces To
spec/01-store.md §1.6 (HLC), ADR-STORE-004, guide/01-store.md §1.2

comments.text:
[AUDIT-R3 HIGH FIX] HLC clock regression handling.

Per spec/01-store.md §1.4.3, when physical clock regresses (wall_time_now < hlc.wall_time):
  1. Keep hlc.wall_time unchanged (do NOT regress)
  2. Increment hlc.logical
  3. If hlc.logical overflows u32: PANIC — this indicates a catastrophic clock failure
     (2^32 logical ticks at the same wall_time is physically impossible in normal operation)

IMPLEMENTATION (Hlc::tick method):
  pub fn tick(&mut self) -> TxId {
      let now = wall_clock_now();
      if now > self.wall_time {
          self.wall_time = now;
          self.logical = 0;
      } else {
          // Clock regression or same-millisecond: increment logical
          self.logical = self.logical.checked_add(1)
              .expect('HLC logical overflow: clock stuck for 2^32 ticks');
      }
      TxId { wall_time: self.wall_time, logical: self.logical, agent: self.agent }
  }

  pub fn merge(&mut self, remote: TxId) -> TxId {
      let now = wall_clock_now();
      if now > self.wall_time && now > remote.wall_time {
          self.wall_time = now;
          self.logical = 0;
      } else if self.wall_time == remote.wall_time {
          self.logical = self.logical.max(remote.logical) + 1;
      } else if remote.wall_time > self.wall_time {
          self.wall_time = remote.wall_time;
          self.logical = remote.logical + 1;
      } else {
          self.logical += 1;
      }
      TxId { wall_time: self.wall_time, logical: self.logical, agent: self.agent }
  }

CRITICAL PROPERTY: TxId::total_order() is monotonically increasing within an agent.
PROOF OBLIGATION: For any sequence of tick() calls, t_i < t_{i+1} in total order.

V:PROP — proptest: tick() sequence is strictly monotone
V:KANI — bounded model check: 1000 tick() calls with arbitrary clock regressions

