[AUDIT-R3 MEDIUM FIX] K_agent(t) — agent knowledge frontier definition.

Per spec/06-seed.md §6.2, the ASSOCIATE phase needs K_agent(t):

  K_agent(t) = the set of entity IDs that agent 'agent' has transacted or queried
               in the current session, up to time t.

CONSTRUCTION:
  K_agent(t) = { e | ∃ datom d ∈ Store : d.entity = e ∧ d.tx.agent = agent ∧ d.tx ≤ t }
             ∪ { e | e was returned by a query in this session }

This is maintained as a growing set during the session:
  pub struct AgentFrontier {
      pub agent: AgentId,
      pub transacted: HashSet<EntityId>,  // entities this agent has written
      pub queried: HashSet<EntityId>,     // entities this agent has read
      pub session_start: TxId,            // beginning of current session
  }

  impl AgentFrontier {
      pub fn knowledge_set(&self) -> HashSet<EntityId> {
          &self.transacted | &self.queried  // union
      }

      pub fn record_transaction(&mut self, tx: &Transaction<Applied>) {
          for datom in tx.datoms() {
              self.transacted.insert(datom.entity);
          }
      }

      pub fn record_query_result(&mut self, results: &ResultSet) {
          for tuple in &results.tuples {
              for value in tuple {
                  if let Value::EntityId(e) = value {
                      self.queried.insert(*e);
                  }
              }
          }
      }
  }

ASSOCIATE uses K_agent(t) to determine which store regions are RELEVANT
to this agent's work (vs. the full store which may contain unrelated datoms).

V:TYPE — AgentFrontier compiles with HashSet operations
V:PROP — knowledge_set() is monotonically non-decreasing during a session

[AUDIT-R3 MEDIUM FIX] ASSOCIATE stage specification.

Per spec/06-seed.md §6.2:

  pub fn associate(
      store: &Store,
      frontier: &AgentFrontier,
      config: &SeedConfig,
  ) -> Vec<(EntityId, f64)> {
      let mut scored: Vec<(EntityId, f64)> = Vec::new();

      // Phase 1: Direct relevance — entities in K_agent(t)
      for entity in frontier.knowledge_set() {
          scored.push((entity, 1.0));  // maximum relevance
      }

      // Phase 2: Keyword expansion — entities sharing attributes with K_agent(t)
      let active_attrs: HashSet<Keyword> = frontier.knowledge_set()
          .iter()
          .flat_map(|e| store.attributes_of(e))
          .collect();

      for entity in store.entities_with_any_attr(&active_attrs) {
          if !frontier.knowledge_set().contains(&entity) {
              let overlap = store.attributes_of(&entity)
                  .intersection(&active_attrs).count() as f64
                  / active_attrs.len() as f64;
              scored.push((entity, overlap * 0.7));  // discounted relevance
          }
      }

      // Phase 3: Graph expansion — entities reachable via Ref edges (1-hop)
      for (entity, score) in scored.clone() {
          for neighbor in store.ref_neighbors(&entity) {
              if !scored.iter().any(|(e, _)| *e == neighbor) {
                  scored.push((neighbor, score * 0.5));  // distance decay
              }
          }
      }

      // Sort by relevance, truncate to top-K
      scored.sort_by(|a, b| b.1.partial_cmp(&a.1).unwrap());
      scored.truncate(config.max_entities);
      scored
  }

RELEVANCE SCORING: Direct (1.0) > Keyword overlap (0.7×) > Graph neighbor (0.5×)
This is a simple relevance model. Stage 1+ can add TF-IDF, embedding similarity, etc.

V:TYPE — associate returns Vec<(EntityId, f64)>
V:PROP — K_agent(t) entities always score ≥ keyword-matched entities
V:PROP — output is sorted by score descending

[AUDIT-R3 MEDIUM FIX] ASSEMBLE stage specification.

Per spec/06-seed.md §6.3:

  pub fn assemble(
      store: &Store,
      scored_entities: &[(EntityId, f64)],
      budget: TokenBudget,
  ) -> AssembledContext {
      let mut sections = Vec::new();
      let mut tokens_used = 0;

      // Section 1: Active Constraints (always included, fixed cost)
      let constraints = assemble_constraints(store);
      tokens_used += constraints.token_count;
      sections.push(constraints);

      // Section 2: Schema Summary
      let schema_section = assemble_schema_summary(store, &scored_entities);
      tokens_used += schema_section.token_count;
      sections.push(schema_section);

      // Section 3-N: Entity sections, ordered by relevance
      for (entity, relevance) in scored_entities {
          if tokens_used >= budget.total { break; }
          let section = assemble_entity_section(store, entity, *relevance);
          if tokens_used + section.token_count <= budget.total {
              tokens_used += section.token_count;
              sections.push(section);
          }
      }

      AssembledContext {
          sections,
          total_tokens: tokens_used,
          budget_remaining: budget.total - tokens_used,
          coverage: compute_coverage(&sections, scored_entities),
          strategy: SeedStrategy::Relevance,
      }
  }

FIVE-PART SEED STRUCTURE (from the original bead):
  Part 1: Project identity + constraints (C1-C7)
  Part 2: Current schema state
  Part 3: Active decisions (ADRs most relevant to scored entities)
  Part 4: Recent transactions (methodology context)
  Part 5: Guidance state (M(t), warnings, suggested focus)

V:TYPE — assemble returns AssembledContext
V:PROP — total_tokens ≤ budget.total (hard constraint)
V:PROP — constraints section always present (never omitted)

[AUDIT-R3 MEDIUM FIX] Merge set-union implementation specification.

  pub fn merge(left: &Store, right: &Store) -> MergeOutcome {
      let mut result_datoms: BTreeSet<Datom> = BTreeSet::new();
      let mut new_count = 0usize;
      let mut dup_count = 0usize;

      // Phase 1: Add all left datoms
      for datom in left.datoms() {
          result_datoms.insert(datom.clone());
      }

      // Phase 2: Add right datoms (dedup via BTreeSet)
      for datom in right.datoms() {
          if result_datoms.insert(datom.clone()) {
              new_count += 1;  // was not in left
          } else {
              dup_count += 1;  // content-addressable duplicate
          }
      }

      // Phase 3: Build result store
      let result = Store::from_datoms(result_datoms);

      // Phase 4: Schema compatibility check
      // (validation only — does not modify datoms)
      let schema_conflicts = check_schema_compatibility(
          left.schema(), right.schema()
      );

      // Phase 5: Detect conflicts for cascade stub
      let conflicts = detect_merge_conflicts(&result);

      MergeOutcome {
          store: result,
          new_datoms: new_count,
          duplicate_datoms: dup_count,
          cascade: MergeCascade {
              conflicts_detected: conflicts.len(),
              resolution_needed: conflicts,
          },
          schema_warnings: schema_conflicts,
      }
  }

KEY PROPERTIES:
  - Commutativity: merge(A, B) == merge(B, A) [same datom set]
  - Associativity: merge(merge(A, B), C) == merge(A, merge(B, C))
  - Idempotency: merge(A, A) == A [dup_count == |A|, new_count == 0]
  - Monotonicity: |merge(A, B)| ≥ max(|A|, |B|)

V:TYPE — merge function compiles as free function (not method)
V:PROP — commutativity holds for random store pairs
V:PROP — idempotency: merge(S, S).store == S

[AUDIT-R3 MEDIUM FIX] Five-step cascade specification.

Per spec/07-merge.md §7.2, the merge cascade is:

  Step 1: SET UNION — datom sets unioned (done in merge() core)
  Step 2: DEDUP — content-addressable identity handles this (BTreeSet)
  Step 3: SCHEMA MERGE — verify schema compatibility

  pub fn check_schema_compatibility(
      left: &Schema,
      right: &Schema,
  ) -> Vec<SchemaWarning> {
      let mut warnings = Vec::new();
      for (keyword, left_attr) in left.iter() {
          if let Some(right_attr) = right.get(keyword) {
              if left_attr.value_type != right_attr.value_type {
                  warnings.push(SchemaWarning::TypeMismatch {
                      attribute: keyword.clone(),
                      left: left_attr.value_type,
                      right: right_attr.value_type,
                  });
              }
          }
      }
      warnings
  }

  Step 4: INDEX REBUILD — LIVE indexes rebuilt from merged datom set
    (Handled by Store::from_datoms which builds all 4 indexes)

  Step 5: CASCADE STUB — emit conflict report for resolution layer

  pub fn detect_merge_conflicts(store: &Store) -> Vec<(EntityId, Keyword)> {
      let mut conflicts = Vec::new();
      // For each (entity, attribute) pair, check if multiple assertions exist
      // from different transactions with no causal ordering
      for (entity, attr) in store.entity_attribute_pairs() {
          let assertions = store.eavt_range(entity, attr)
              .filter(|d| d.op == Op::Assert && !is_retracted(store, d))
              .collect::<Vec<_>>();
          if assertions.len() > 1 {
              // Check if any pair is concurrent (no causal ordering)
              for i in 0..assertions.len() {
                  for j in i+1..assertions.len() {
                      if are_concurrent(store, assertions[i].tx, assertions[j].tx) {
                          conflicts.push((entity, attr.clone()));
                          break;
                      }
                  }
              }
          }
      }
      conflicts
  }

