[AUDIT-R3 MEDIUM FIX] Persistence bridge specification.

The persistence bridge is the IO boundary between Store (pure) and Layout (filesystem):

  pub struct PersistenceBridge {
      layout: DiskLayout,
  }

  impl PersistenceBridge {
      pub fn new(root: &Path) -> Result<Self, BraidError> {
          let layout = DiskLayout::init(root)?;
          Ok(Self { layout })
      }

      /// Load store from disk
      pub fn load(&self) -> Result<Store, BraidError> {
          self.layout.load_all()
      }

      /// Flush a committed transaction to disk, then apply to store
      pub fn persist_and_apply(
          &self,
          store: &mut Store,
          tx: Transaction<Committed>,
      ) -> Result<TxReport, BraidError> {
          // 1. Write transaction file to disk (durable)
          self.layout.write_tx(&tx)?;
          // 2. Apply to in-memory store
          let report = tx.apply(store)
              .map_err(BraidError::Kernel)?;
          Ok(report)
      }

      /// Merge another store directory
      pub fn merge_from(&self, other: &Path) -> Result<MergeOutcome, BraidError> {
          self.layout.merge_directories(other)
      }
  }

ORDERING: Disk write BEFORE in-memory apply.
  If disk write fails → store unchanged (consistent).
  If apply fails after disk write → transaction file exists but store doesn't have it.
  On next load, the transaction will be loaded from disk (crash recovery via replay).

This is the crash recovery model from ADR-PROTOCOL-003: replay from disk on startup.

V:TYPE — PersistenceBridge compiles with DiskLayout
V:PROP — persist_and_apply is idempotent (replay safe)

[AUDIT-R3 MEDIUM FIX] Phi(S) implementation specification.

  pub fn compute_phi(store: &Store) -> CoherenceReport {
      let goals = query_goals(store);       // entities with :goal/* attributes
      let invs = query_invariants(store);   // entities with :inv/* attributes
      let tests = query_test_results(store); // entities with :test/* attributes

      // Intent-Spec divergence: goals without corresponding INVs
      let d_is = goals.iter()
          .filter(|g| !invs.iter().any(|i| traces_to(store, i, g)))
          .count() as f64 / goals.len().max(1) as f64;

      // Spec-Impl divergence: INVs without passing tests
      let d_si = invs.iter()
          .filter(|i| !tests.iter().any(|t| covers(store, t, i) && t.passed))
          .count() as f64 / invs.len().max(1) as f64;

      // Intent-Impl divergence: goals without transitive test coverage
      let d_ii = goals.iter()
          .filter(|g| !has_transitive_test_coverage(store, g))
          .count() as f64 / goals.len().max(1) as f64;

      let phi = 1.0 - (d_is + d_si + d_ii) / 3.0;

      CoherenceReport {
          phi,
          intent_spec_divergence: d_is,
          spec_impl_divergence: d_si,
          intent_impl_divergence: d_ii,
          formality_gradient: compute_formality_gradient(store),
          convergence_trend: compute_trend(store),
      }
  }

QUERY PATTERNS (Datalog):
  goals: [:find ?g :where [?g :goal/traces-to _]]
  invs: [:find ?i :where [?i :inv/id _]]
  tests: [:find ?t :where [?t :test/inv-id _] [?t :test/passed true]]
  traces_to: [:find ?i :where [?i :inv/traces-to ?g]]
  covers: [:find ?t :where [?t :test/inv-id ?inv-id] [?i :inv/id ?inv-id]]

V:TYPE — compute_phi compiles, returns CoherenceReport
V:PROP — phi ∈ [0.0, 1.0]
V:PROP — phi = 1.0 iff d_is = d_si = d_ii = 0.0

[AUDIT-R3 MEDIUM FIX] Formality gradient specification.

Per spec/18-trilateral.md §18.3, the formality gradient measures how 'formal'
each schema layer's specification is:

  pub struct FormalityGradient {
      pub levels: [f64; 6],  // L0..L5 scores, each ∈ [0.0, 1.0]
      pub monotone: bool,    // true if levels[0] ≥ levels[1] ≥ ... ≥ levels[5]
  }

  impl FormalityGradient {
      pub fn compute(store: &Store) -> Self {
          let levels = [
              formality_score(store, SchemaLayer::L0_Foundation),
              formality_score(store, SchemaLayer::L1_AgentProvenance),
              formality_score(store, SchemaLayer::L2_SpecElements),
              formality_score(store, SchemaLayer::L3_Lifecycle),
              formality_score(store, SchemaLayer::L4_Intelligence),
              formality_score(store, SchemaLayer::L5_UserDefined),
          ];
          let monotone = levels.windows(2).all(|w| w[0] >= w[1]);
          Self { levels, monotone }
      }
  }

  fn formality_score(store: &Store, layer: SchemaLayer) -> f64 {
      let attrs = store.schema().attributes_at_layer(layer);
      if attrs.is_empty() { return 0.0; }
      let with_inv = attrs.iter()
          .filter(|a| has_invariant_coverage(store, a))
          .count();
      let with_test = attrs.iter()
          .filter(|a| has_test_coverage(store, a))
          .count();
      // Weighted: 40% INV coverage + 60% test coverage
      (0.4 * with_inv as f64 + 0.6 * with_test as f64) / attrs.len() as f64
  }

EXPECTED GRADIENT: Foundation (L0) should be most formal → User (L5) least formal.
  If monotone is false, it indicates a formality inversion (a diagnostic signal).
  Guidance warns: 'Formality inversion at layer {N}: consider adding INVs/tests.'

V:TYPE — FormalityGradient compiles
V:PROP — all level scores ∈ [0.0, 1.0]
V:PROP — genesis store has levels[0] = 1.0 (foundation fully specified)

