[AUDIT-R3 MEDIUM FIX] Causal order partial order specification.

DEFINITION: The causal order ≤_c on transactions is defined by:
  tx₁ ≤_c tx₂ iff tx₁ ∈ predecessors*(tx₂)
  where predecessors*(tx) is the transitive closure of the predecessor relation.

STRUCTURE: (Transactions, ≤_c) is a PARTIAL ORDER (not total):
  P1: Reflexive — tx ≤_c tx (every tx is its own predecessor, vacuously)
  P2: Antisymmetric — tx₁ ≤_c tx₂ ∧ tx₂ ≤_c tx₁ ⇒ tx₁ = tx₂
      (no causal cycles — guaranteed by HLC monotonicity)
  P3: Transitive — tx₁ ≤_c tx₂ ∧ tx₂ ≤_c tx₃ ⇒ tx₁ ≤_c tx₃

CONCURRENT TRANSACTIONS: tx₁ ∥ tx₂ iff ¬(tx₁ ≤_c tx₂) ∧ ¬(tx₂ ≤_c tx₁)
  Concurrent transactions are the source of conflicts.
  The conflict predicate (spec/04-resolution.md) detects them.

RELATIONSHIP TO HLC: The HLC total order is a LINEARIZATION of the causal order.
  tx₁ ≤_c tx₂ ⇒ tx₁.total_order() < tx₂.total_order()
  But NOT the converse: tx₁.total_order() < tx₂.total_order() does NOT imply tx₁ ≤_c tx₂.
  (Two independent agents may have ordered HLC timestamps without causal connection.)

IMPLEMENTATION: Predecessors stored as datom attributes on transaction entities:
  [tx_entity, :tx/predecessors, predecessor_tx_id, tx_entity, assert]

  fn is_causally_before(store: &Store, tx1: TxId, tx2: TxId) -> bool {
      // BFS/DFS on predecessor graph
      let mut visited = HashSet::new();
      let mut queue = VecDeque::from([tx2]);
      while let Some(current) = queue.pop_front() {
          if current == tx1 { return true; }
          if visited.insert(current) {
              for pred in store.predecessors(current) {
                  queue.push_back(pred);
              }
          }
      }
      false
  }

V:PROP — is_causally_before is a partial order (reflexive, antisymmetric, transitive)
V:KANI — no causal cycles in any store with ≤ 10 transactions

